–1323","–Female":"Deceased","2 February 1323":"2 February 1323","1315":"1315","before 1323":"before 1323","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","about 1286":"about 1286","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roydon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Royden  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Royden","meanings":["English: locative name from Roydon (Essex), Roydon near Diss (Norfolk), Roydon near King’s Lynn (Norfolk), or Roydon Drift (Suffolk)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":40,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Roydon was born in 1275, in England as the son of William Roydon and End of line. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Raymes. He died on 2 February 1323, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1275–2 February 1323":"1275–2. veebruar 1323","1275–1323":"1275–1323","–1323":"–1323","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1300–1343":"1300–1343","1250–1323":"1250–1323","–Female":"Surnud","2 February 1323":"2. veebruar 1323","1315":"1315","before 1323":"enne 1323","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","about 1286":"umbes 1286","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"1275–2 February 1323":"1275–2. helmikuuta 1323","1275–1323":"1275–1323","–1323":"–1323","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1300–1343":"1300–1343","1250–1323":"1250–1323","–Female":"Kuollut","2 February 1323":"2. helmikuuta 1323","1315":"1315","before 1323":"ennen vuotta 1323","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","about 1286":"noin 1286","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fr":{"1275–2 February 1323":"1275–2 février 1323","1275–1323":"1275–1323","–1323":"–1323","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1300–1343":"1300–1343","1250–1323":"1250–1323","–Female":"Décédée","2 February 1323":"2 février 1323","1315":"1315","before 1323":"avant 1323","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","about 1286":"environ 1286","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Roydon est né en 1275, à Angleterre, fils de William Roydon et End of line. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Alice Raymes. Il est décédé le 2 février 1323, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 48 ans."},"de":{"1275–2 Febr